{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585050","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585050"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:01:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:01:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14844"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14844","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14844"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.11,0.22,0.22,0.36]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7535"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58959"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7535","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7535"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14844"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44370"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5651"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18438"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18552"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58959"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following blood products has the highest cost per unit?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Red cells leucodeplete","Pooled platelets","Apheresis platelets","Fresh frozen plasma","Cryoprecipitate"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBlood products vary significantly in cost due to differences in collection methods, processing requirements, and shelf life. \u003Cstrong\u003EApheresis platelets\u003C/strong\u003E are the most expensive blood product due to the complex collection process, which involves a single donor being connected to an apheresis machine for 1-2 hours. The platelets have a short shelf life of only 5-7 days, adding to the cost.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPooled platelets\u003C/strong\u003E are less expensive than apheresis platelets as they are derived from multiple whole blood donations that are processed to extract platelets. However, they still require careful processing and have the same short shelf life.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERed cells leucodeplete\u003C/strong\u003E are relatively less expensive as they can be stored for up to 42 days and the collection process is simpler. The leucodepletion process adds some cost but is now standard for all red cell products in many countries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFresh frozen plasma\u003C/strong\u003E is less expensive than cellular products as it can be stored frozen for up to one year and the processing is relatively straightforward.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECryoprecipitate\u003C/strong\u003E is a derived plasma product that is relatively inexpensive to produce as it is a by-product of fresh frozen plasma preparation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the relative costs of blood products is important for resource stewardship in transfusion medicine, although clinical need should always be the primary consideration in transfusion decisions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Apheresis platelets are the most expensive blood product due to the complex collection process and short shelf-life.","Understanding blood product costs is important for resource stewardship in transfusion medicine.","Apheresis platelets are collected from a single donor, while pooled platelets are derived from multiple whole blood donations."],"references":["Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., Fausto, N., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (2014). Robbins and Cotran pathologic basis of disease, professional edition e-book. Elsevier health sciences","National Clinical Guideline Centre (UK). Blood Transfusion. London: National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE); 2015 Nov. (NICE Guideline, No. 24.) 16, Cryoprecipitate: thresholds and targets. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK338779/","Van der Meer, P. F.. Apheresis versus whole\u2010blood\u2010derived platelets: pros and cons. ISBT Science Series, 7(1), 112-116. 2012. Available from: https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1751-2824.2012.01586.x","Ness, P. M., \u0026 Daou, L. Single donor platelets versus whole blood derived platelets: are they the same?. Annals of Blood, 5. 2020. Available from: https://aob.amegroups.org/article/view/6140/html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44370"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14844"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44370","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44370"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-03T23:13:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-05T19:10:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7535"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58959"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"upd